The Dewey Decimal System (1876): While working as a student assistant in the library of Amherst College, Dewey devised the Dewey Decimal Classification 
(DDC)
 system at the remarkably young age of 24. His brilliant insight was to use decimals to create a hierarchical, infinitely expandable system that could shelve books by subject. This replaced far more cumbersome and less logical methods, making libraries vastly more accessible to the public.

Other Contributions: His drive for efficiency and standardization didn't stop there. He was a co-founder of the American Library Association (ALA) and served as its secretary. He also helped establish the first school for librarianship, the Columbia School of Library Economy, in 1887. He was even a founding member of the Lake Placid Club and an advocate for spelling reform (which is why he dropped the 'le' from Melville and 'ugh' from DuiÃÂ¢Ã¢âÂ¬Ã¢â¬Âthough we now spell it "Dewey").

Complex Legacy: It is important to note that while Dewey's professional contributions were monumental, his personal legacy is complex and marred. He held and actively promoted racist, antisemitic, and sexist views, which led to him being ostracized by several professional organizations later in his life. Modern discussions of Dewey rightly acknowledge both his transformative system and his harmful personal beliefs.

