Part 2: The Socratic Method
Your desire to use "well-directed questions to transmit [your] education" is the very heart of the Socratic Method. It is a powerful form of cooperative dialogue, not a lecture.

What it is:
The Socratic Method is a technique of inquiry and discussion, named after the classical Greek philosopher Socrates, who used it to explore complex ideas and expose the underlying assumptions in people's beliefs. He famously claimed, "I know that I know nothing," and used questioning to help others discover knowledge for themselves.

How it works:
Instead of stating facts, a teacher (or a participant in a dialogue) uses a series of carefully crafted, open-ended questions to:

Probe underlying beliefs: Challenge unexamined assumptions.

Stimulate critical thinking: Force the respondent to analyze and justify their position.

Illuminate contradictions: Help someone see where their logic may be inconsistent.

Arrive at a deeper understanding: Guide the person to construct their own knowledge and reach a conclusion logically.

A Simple Example:

Statement: "Courage is never being afraid."

Socratic Questioning: "So if a soldier charges into battle feeling no fear, that is courage. But what about a soldier who is terrified, yet still performs their duty to protect their comrades? Is that not also courage, or perhaps even a greater form of it?"

Result: The definition of "courage" is refined from the absence of fear to acting rightly in the face of fear.

