Part 1: The Economic Engine (330)
Supply and Demand & The Free Market:
This is the core mechanism of most modern economies. Demand is how much of a product or service is desired by buyers. Supply is how much the market can offer. The relationship between them determines the price.

If demand exceeds supply, prices rise, incentivizing producers to make more.

If supply exceeds demand, prices fall, encouraging more buyers.
A Free Market Economy is one where prices are set by this voluntary exchange, with minimal government interference.

From Barter to Money:
Barter is the direct exchange of goods and services (e.g., a chicken for a pair of shoes). Its limitation is the "double coincidence of wants"ÃÂ¢Ã¢âÂ¬Ã¢â¬Âyou must find someone who has what you want and wants what you have.
Money emerged as a solution, acting as:

A Medium of Exchange: It is universally accepted for payment.

A Unit of Account: It provides a standard measure of value.

A Store of Value: It can be saved and used in the future.

The Historical Rise of Capitalism:
After the Maritime Age (1500s+), European nations amassed vast wealth (gold, silver) and new resources from the Americas and Asia. This "primitive accumulation of capital" funded new ventures. The Commercial Revolution saw the rise of joint-stock companies (like the British East India Company), which pooled capital for large, risky voyages. This evolved into the Industrial Revolution, where capital was invested in machinery and factories. Capitalism, as a system where private owners control trade and industry for profit, became the dominant economic model.

