The History of Science: A Convergence of Worlds
The story of science is one of slow accumulation, often fueled by the meeting of different cultures.

The Islamic Golden Age (c. 8th-14th centuries): As Europe was in its early Middle Ages, the Abbasid Caliphate in Baghdad became the world's scientific center. Scholars like Al-Khwarizmi (whose name gives us "algorithm") systematized algebra (from al-jabr, "the reunion of broken parts"). They preserved and expanded upon Greek knowledge (Plato, Aristotle, Ptolemy) and made breakthroughs in optics, medicine, and chemistry. This knowledge would later flow back into Europe.

The Renaissance (14th-17th centuries): A rebirth of classical learning in Europe, fueled by patrons like the Medici family. This was the age of Leonardo da Vinci, the ultimate Renaissance manÃÂ¢Ã¢âÂ¬Ã¢â¬Âan artist, engineer, and scientist who studied anatomy, flight, and hydraulics. Michelangelo embodied the fusion of art, humanism, and scientific observation of the human form. This was also the time of Suleiman the Magnificent, under whose rule the Ottoman Empire was a powerful counterpart and bridge between East and West.

