The World of Chemistry (540)
Chemistry is the study of matter and its transformations.

The Atom & Molecules: John Dalton (early 1800s) proposed the first modern atomic theory, that all matter is composed of tiny, indivisible particles called atoms. Molecules are groups of atoms bonded together.

The Periodic Table: Dmitri Mendeleev's brilliant organization of the elements based on atomic weight (and later, atomic number), which allowed him to predict properties of undiscovered elements.

Acids and Bases: Two fundamental classes of chemicals that react with each other in predictable ways.

The Chemical Equation: A symbolic representation of a chemical reaction, which must be balanced according to the law of conservation of mass.

The Mole: A central concept in chemistry. It is not a small animal, but a unit of measurement that represents a specific number of particles (6.022 x 10^23, Avogadro's number), allowing chemists to "count" atoms and molecules by weighing them.

Chemical Bonds: The forces that hold atoms together.

Ionic Bonds: Formed when electrons are transferred from one atom to another, creating oppositely charged ions that attract.

Covalent Bonds: Formed when atoms share electrons.

