A Journey Through the 700s - Arts & Recreation
710 - 720: The Art of Space - Civic Planning & Architecture
This is where art meets the public sphere, creating the environment we live in.

Ancient Greek Architecture: The Greeks perfected the post-and-lintel system and gave us the three classical orders:

Doric: Sturdy, plain top (capital). Seen in the Parthenon. Masculine strength.

Ionic: Scroll-like capitals. More graceful and feminine.

Corinthian: Elaborate capitals decorated with acanthus leaves. The most ornate.

The Etruscan Arch: Before Rome, the Etruscans in Italy mastered the arch. The Romans would later adopt and perfect this structure, which allowed them to build larger, stronger buildings like aqueducts and the Colosseum.

The Dome: While the Romans perfected the massive dome (see the Pantheon), the Greeks had used it in smaller structures. The dome became a central feature in later Byzantine (e.g., Hagia Sophia) and Islamic architecture (e.g., the Dome of the Rock).

The Islamic Pointed Arch: A crucial architectural innovation from the Islamic world. It is structurally stronger and more elegant than the rounded Roman arch. This form was encountered by Europeans during the Crusades and brought back to Europe.

Gothic Architecture: The pointed arch was the key that unlocked Gothic architecture. It allowed for taller, lighter buildings with vast stained-glass windows that told biblical stories to a largely illiterate population, turning entire cathedrals into "Bibles of glass and stone." This style flourished in the High Middle Ages.

The Architecture of the Castle & Gunpowder: Early castles were tall stone towers (keeps). With the introduction of gunpowder and cannons in the late Middle Ages, castle architecture changed dramatically. Walls became lower and thicker (to resist cannon fire) and were designed with angled bastions. Gunpowder made the high, thin walls of older castles obsolete.

